">mass</a> equal to 200&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milli=
gram" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Milligram">mg</a> (0.00705&nbsp;<a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ounce" title=3D"Ounce">oz</a>; 0.00643&n=
bsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_ounce" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Troy ounce">ozt</a>), which is used for measuring <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gemstone" title=3D"Gemstone">gemstones</a> and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearl" title=3D"Pearl">pearls</a>=
.
The current definition, sometimes known as the <b>metric carat</b>, was ado=
pted in 1907 at the Fourth <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General=
_Conference_on_Weights_and_Measures" title=3D"General Conference on Weights=
 and Measures">General Conference on Weights and Measures</a>,<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Science1908_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-Science1908-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-CGPM4_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Carat_(mass)#cite_note-CGPM4-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and soon afterwards in many coun=
tries around the world.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>i<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The =
carat is divisible into 100 <i>points</i> of 2&nbsp;mg. Other subdivisions,=
 and slightly different mass values, have been used in the past in differen=
t locations.
</p><p>In terms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamond" title=
=3D"Diamond">diamonds</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parag=
on_(diamond)" title=3D"Paragon (diamond)">paragon</a> is a flawless stone o=
f at least 100 carats (20&nbsp;g).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ahdparagon_4-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_n=
ote-ahdparagon-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_National_Stand=
ards_Institute" title=3D"American National Standards Institute">ANSI</a> <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_Data_Interchange" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electronic Data Interchange">X.12 EDI</a> standar=
d abbreviation for the carat is <b>CD</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-5=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCarat_(mass)&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>First attested in English in the mid-15th century, the word <i>carat</i>=
 comes from Italian <i>carato</i>, which comes from <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Arabic_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Arabic la=
nguage">Arabic</a> (<i>q=C4=ABr=C4=81=E1=B9=AD</i>; =D9=82=D9=8A=D8=B1=D8=
=A7=D8=B7), in turn borrowed from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Greek_language" title=3D"Greek language">Greek</a> <i>ker=C3=A1tion</i> =CE=
=BA=CE=B5=CF=81=CE=AC=CF=84=CE=B9=CE=BF=CE=BD '<a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Carob" title=3D"Carob">carob</a> seed',<sup id=3D"cite_ref-har=
per_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat=
_(mass)#cite_note-harper-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Liddel_7-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_n=
ote-Liddel-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> a di=
minutive of <i>keras</i> 'horn'.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-9"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> It was a unit of weight, equal to 1/1728 (1/12<sup>3</sup>) of a pound (=
see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mina_(unit)" title=3D"Mina (un=
it)">Mina (unit)</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Liddel_7-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-Liddel-7"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
harper_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
rat_(mass)#cite_note-harper-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCarat_(mass)&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Carob seeds have been used throughout history to measure jewelry, becaus=
e it was believed that there was little variance in their mass distribution=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, this was a factu=
al inaccuracy, as their mass varies about as much as seeds of other species=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the past, each country had its own carat. It was often used for w=
eighing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold" title=3D"Gold">gold<=
/a>. Beginning in the 1570s, it was used to measure weights of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamond" title=3D"Diamond">diamonds</a>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-harper_6-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-harper-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Standardization">Standardiz=
ation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCarat_=
(mass)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Standardiz=
ation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>An 'international carat' of 205 milligrams was proposed in 1871 by the S=
yndical Chamber of Jewellers, etc., in Paris, and accepted in 1877 by the S=
yndical Chamber of Diamond Merchants in Paris. A metric carat of 200 millig=
rams is exactly one-fifth of a gram and had often been suggested in various=
 countries,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM4_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-CGPM4-2"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and =
was finally proposed by the International Committee of Weights and Measures=
, and unanimously accepted<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM4_2-2" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-CGPM4-2">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> at the fourth sexennial General Conference of the Metric Convent=
ion held in Paris in October 1907. It was soon made compulsory by law in Fr=
ance, but uptake of the new carat was slower in England, where its use was =
allowed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weights_and_Measure=
s_Acts_(UK)#19th_century" title=3D"Weights and Measures Acts (UK)">Weights =
and Measures (Metric System) Act of 1897</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_n=
ote-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
