<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"UK_Board_of_Trade">UK Board=
 of Trade</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCa=
rat_(mass)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: UK Boa=
rd of Trade"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D=
"United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a> the original <b><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Board_of_Trade" title=3D"Board of Trade">Board of Trade</=
a> carat</b> was exactly <span class=3D"frac">3<span class=3D"sr-only">+</s=
pan><span class=3D"num">1647</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">9691</span>=
</span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grain_(unit)" title=3D"Gra=
in (unit)">grains</a> (~3.170&nbsp;grains =3D ~205&nbsp;mg);<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat=
_(mass)#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>ii<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> in 1888, the Board of Trade carat was cha=
nged to exactly <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:=
TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">3<span class=3D"sr-only">+=
</span><span class=3D"num">17</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">101</span>=
</span> grains (~3.168&nbsp;grains =3D ~205&nbsp;mg).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)=
#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>iii<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Despite it being a non-metric unit, a number of=
 metric countries have used this unit for its limited range of application.
</p><p>The Board of Trade carat was divisible into four <i>diamond grains</=
i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>iv<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but measurements were t=
ypically made in multiples of <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" hr=
ef=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=
=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"de=
n">64</span></span> carat.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Refiners'_carats"><span id=
=3D"Refiners.27_carats"></span>Refiners' carats</h3><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCarat_(mass)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Refiners' carats"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There were also two varieties of <i>refiners' carats</i> once used in th=
e United Kingdom=E2=80=94the <b>pound carat</b> and the <b>ounce carat</b>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>v=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_(mass)#Troy_pound" title=3D"Pound (mass)">pound tro=
y</a> was divisible into 24 <i>pound carats</i> of 240 grains troy each; th=
e pound carat was divisible into four <i>pound grains</i> of 60 grains troy=
 each; and the pound grain was divisible into four <i>pound quarters</i> of=
 15 grains troy each. Likewise, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Ounce#International_troy_ounce" title=3D"Ounce">ounce troy</a> was divisi=
ble into 24 <i>ounce carats</i> of 20 grains troy each; the ounce carat was=
 divisible into four <i>ounce grains</i> of 5 grains troy each; and the oun=
ce grain was divisible into four <i>ounce quarters</i> of <link rel=3D"mw-d=
eduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span=
 class=3D"frac">1<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</spa=
n>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">4</span></span> grains troy each.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
arat_(mass)#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Greco-Roman">Greco-Roman</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCarat_(mass)&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Greco-Roman"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>The <i>solidus</i> was also a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
oman_Empire" title=3D"Roman Empire">Roman</a> weight unit. There is literar=
y evidence that the weight of 72&nbsp;coins of the type called <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solidus_(coin)" title=3D"Solidus (coin)">=
solidus</a></i> was exactly 1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roma=
n_pound" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Roman pound">Roman pound</a>, and t=
hat the weight of 1&nbsp;<i>solidus</i> was 24&nbsp;<i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siliqua" title=3D"Siliqua">siliquae</a></i>. The weigh=
t of a Roman pound is generally believed to have been 327.45&nbsp;g or poss=
ibly up to 5&nbsp;g less. Therefore, the metric equivalent of 1 <i>siliqua<=
/i> was approximately 189&nbsp;mg. The Greeks had a similar unit of the sam=
e value.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-grierson_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note-grierson-20"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>Gold <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fineness" title=3D"Fin=
eness">fineness</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fineness#Ka=
rat" title=3D"Fineness">carats</a> comes from carats and grains of gold in =
a solidus of coin. The conversion rates 1&nbsp;solidus =3D 24&nbsp;carats, =
1&nbsp;carat =3D 4&nbsp;grains still stand.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carat_(mass)#cite_note=
-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Woolhouse's <i>Measures, Weights and Moneys of All Nations=
